Dorman Products' CEO is ill 

 

Updated: November 14, 2008 — 4:00 PM EST




Facebook icon
0Share


Twitter icon
Tweet


Tumblr icon

Tumblr


Mail icon
Email

 
 








 
  








 
 



  by Mike Armstrong, Inquirer Columnist
      	  	           Mail icon
 marmstrong@phillynews.com  
 
 
 
 
 

Dorman Products Inc., the Colmar-based maker of automotive replacement parts, said its CEO is "receiving treatment for an illness."



Richard N. Berman, who co-founded the company originally known as R&B Inc. in 1978, told employees today that he would continue to serve as CEO.
Shares of Dorman closed down $1.14, or 9 percent, to $11.13 on Friday.



 


The company said in a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission that Berman "may not be able to provide full time service" to Dorman. The nature of the illness was not disclosed.
The company goes on to say that if he can't, "his duties will be performed by other members of senior management."
Berman's brother, Stephen, is president and a co-founder of Dorman.


According to the company's proxy statement from earlier this year, Richard Berman was 51 years old as of March 28.
As of the end of 2007, the company had 1,005 employees worldwide. It had net income of $19.2 million, or $1.06 per share, on net sales of $327.7 million for 2007.








 

Published:  November 14, 2008 — 4:00 PM EST

                                                  The Philadelphia Inquirer
                        
 
 



